[00:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All right, YouTube. What is good? It\'s your boy Rebel back with another video. And today we are taking a look at A Sim Flux 2 for Flux Klein 9B base. So, a little bit about the model. A Sim Flow'

[00:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stands for asymmetric flow modeling. A rank asymmetric velocity parameterization that restricts noise prediction to a low rank subspace while keeping data prediction full'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dimensional. So, the big problem with pixel space models traditionally generating images directly in a raw pixel space instead of utilizing like a compressed latent or VAE slows a system'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to a crawl and the transformer wastes almost all of its compute trying to predict high dimension noise rather than focusing the actual image data. So, this architectural trick kind of breaks the'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'velocity prediction task into two parts and keeps the image data full resolution but compresses the noise prediction into a tight low ranking subspace. By isolating the high noise to a small'

[01:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'patchwise low rank mathematical space, the model doesn\'t have to guess any random pixel determination. So, it can like dedicate its processing power to directly rendering shapes, sharpness,'

[01:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and like following prompt adherence. And this technique provides a direct mathematical bridge to fine-tuning a pre-trained latent into a fully uncompressed pixel space. It lines up the low rank pixel patches with the'

[01:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'existing latent space and it just focuses on the sharpening of the raw textures. So, when comparing this to the regular base model for 9B, this actually completely outperforms it on visual'

[01:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'realism. So, and that\'s on multiple benchmarks. So, this model really benefits from having sharp textures and, you know, good visual clarity. So, to get started, you\'re going to need a'

[02:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'custom node set by 9 XZ. It\'s really simple to get it installed, and we will do that now. So, you\'re going to pull up your custom node directory, and you\'re going to click the address bar, and then'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re going to type CMD and hit enter. And that\'s going to bring up a command prompt inside your custom node directory. And then you are going to come to the link in the description in the workflow. You will find this Git'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Clone command. You will right-click and copy this. And then you will come back to the command prompt and right-click again to paste it, and then you will hit enter. I will not do this because I already'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have the folder, so I do not need to do this. But after you have let this install the custom nodes, you can just X out of the command prompt, and you are done with the custom node set, and then you can download your model of choice,'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your encoder of choice. So, for the encoders, we actually have a Guff encoder if you have extremely low VRAM. Um and then we have an FP4 and an FP8 for the higher scales. At the bottom'

[03:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, you have a required adapter Laura, which sets the model into the pixel space. So, you will need to put that in your Laura\'s folder. Everything else is self-explanatory.'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And after you have downloaded the models, you can then download the workflow and then punch it into Comfy, and it will look something like this. So, starting on the left here, we have our load diffusion model and our U-Net hosting our model file.'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We have our clip or our Guff clip loader hosting our Qwen text encoder on the Flux 2 architecture running on our CPU to save the for the model. Over here, we'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have the A Sim Flux latent node. You can just leave this closed. Here we have our A Sim Flux apply adapter node, which applies our adapter Laura. Moving down, we have our positive and negative'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompting coding nodes, our resolution nodes, and our K sampler. In our K sampler, we are running a step count of 38 with a CFG of four. And then up here, I just have the decode node that is'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specialized for the workflow. closed just because it saves space. With that being said, that accounts for the workflow. So, I do have some examples to show you guys, and we will be taking a look at those right now. So, for my first test, I ran the usual subject'

